I've updated this forecast to 98% probability of the meeting happening (in Singapore), based on hoopla, hotels chosen, and the juggernaut energy released. It would be nearly impossible to get the elephant back in the barn now, but as I have said before, Trump does not really have agency here - Kim has. I can't see value to Kim in cancelling. Trump wants to appear salvific to his base and to the world. The mainstream media will present the meeting as historic, which it is. There may be no substance to come out of the meeting, i.e., nothing more than cordiality and nothing regarding nuclear disarmament. See, for example, press releases re "It may take many meetings.." https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-usa-trump-interview-exclus/exclusive-trump-nuclear-deal-may-take-more-than-one-meeting-with-north-koreas-kim-idUSKCN1IW2CQ. As for Kim having agency, not Trump, Trump says he wants "Pyongyang to dismantle its nuclear weapons program as quickly as possible under any agreement." Ibid. IMHO Kim has no good reason to speedily dismantle, and "as quickly as possible" is vague. See, for example, Brown v Board of Education, 1954, "with all due deliberate speed." Trump has "dangled aid," per this morning's New York Times, but "... the North has been clear that it will not trade its nuclear arms for American aid." https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/01/world/asia/trump-north-korea-economic-aid.html. Why should they? China has been illegally providing North Korea with oil at least since 2017 https://www.vox.com/world/2017/12/28/16825434/trump-north-korea-oil-china, and China can tell the UN Security Council what to do with its sanctions - given the Belt And Road project by which China provides goods to all Asia and Europe, and the $1+ trillion the USA owes China https://www.thebalance.com/u-s-debt-to-china-how-much-does-it-own-3306355. It appears that North Korea has trade with China, doesn't need US aid, Trump's "deal" comes out of a previous century, What, then, is the value to Kim of taking this meeting? He gains great Face.

Kim has been speaking to so many other groups and prefers long term denuclearization and I'm beginning to wonder if he's likely to hedge the coming meeting. In fact, not declaring that he is still willing/planning to still meet in Signapore at the previously planned June meeting (and has said only that he's still generally willing to continue discussions) suggests that he has reservations.

With uncertainty, I think they will meet in June in Singapore, as previously planned. It is more difficult to apply standardized analysis tools to the Trump administration than it is to other institutions, because the predictable drivers of events for the Trump administration are (1) Trump's fragile ego; (2) Trump's lack of impulse control; (3) Trump's perspective on other people; (4) Trump's lack of agency. In practice, this leads me to think that Trump wants the meeting to take place as previously planned - in June, in Singapore - because I read Trump as seeing this as his Winning 100%. He gets to appear to his base as having forced Kim Jong Un to do Trump's bidding entirely, even after Trump publicly refused to meet and blamed Kim. Now, Trump can appear to himself and to his base to have accepted Kim's agreement to what Trump wants. I think that Trump does not want to give the meeting to any other location because he wants to appear as though he is getting Kim to agree to Trump's original terms, Singapore in June. The appearance is Key. There is some chance that Kim will decline to meet under these conditions, because he may want to cause Trump to lose face. But Kim can only do this if he does not lose face in declining to meet. For now, that would be tough - but the Trump administration is famous for snatching defeat from the jaws of victory, so in the coming 2 weeks, T or one of his team could say/do something that gives Kim the perfect excuse to cancel. It might be that Pompeo and others have the good sense to try to keep utterance and event from queering the deal at this point. But Trump has poor impulse control, and some of the planned navy exercises or other events can add up to another calamity. I think the ball is in Kim's court. I think his goal is to get public approval, which translates to money and trade and a huge improvement in Face. If Kim can make some good deals with South Korea and China between now and the proposed meeting time, he can exercise his option to cost Trump face with less cost to himself. But it won't be easy.

Here's the question I keep thinking about: If Trump & Kim don't end up meeting in July (and it's postponed short term or indefinitely), can Kim get what he needs from his neighbors (SKorea, China, others) what he can't get from the US - some economic wiggle room with a slow dismantling or negotiated reduction in nuclear testing/expansion? I don't see Japan jumping for this since they will probably rely more and more on the US being the closest to DPRK and their possible missile attacks. But S. Korea has a strong national motivation to see if Kim means what he says and take it in good faith and hope they don't take a huge loss. And China has very little need to worry about what the US will do if Trump and Kim don't meet. A year ago I'd have said that no way would negotiations of any kind continue (outside of DPRK and China) if the US wasn't involved, but Trump is moving up the timeline of power shifts 5 or 10 years into the near present since he won't really play by anyone else's game but his own. And I think that Kim has reason to hold out for what he wants (less pressure, more ceremony and hope) or even to pull back and get the US into a less aggressive bargaining position (less aggressive than Trump was last week, certainly). But if there's a real possibility that regional powers would entertain private negotiations without a big summit, I wonder if Kim's best choice isn't to pull back and dither until the summit doesn't happen and other communication lines become open. Big if. East Asia policy without the US is tricky, and the precedent will be hard to buck. So I'd guess the realistic chances of such a thing happening are less than 10-20, or less. Also, Trump really wants the summit and probably will keep working toward it without publicly backing down in any direct way. North Korea still wants the talks, or the plans for talks, or they'd have backed out with a hard line already. And their delays in responding to US/Trump comments are just slow enough that I feel like it's more maneuvering than hard line response.

North Korea's foreign policy modus operandi has remained remarkably consistent and predictable since the Sino-Soviet split in 1956 when Kim Il Sung learned he could play the Soviets and the Chinese off each other to maximize the aid, concessions, and subsidies they received. As a result, North Korea was one of the most economically viable Eastern Bloc states until the 1990s. This pattern of behavior carried over into the post-Cold War years when the late Kim and then his son Kim Jong Il discovered they could just as easily play the US and South Korea off each other, especially when Seoul had a liberal government that was eager to improve inter-Korean relations and Washington had a more hawkish, conservative regime. Typically, the North would accomplish this by reaching an agreement on paper with the allies in exchange for concessions and then, once those concessions came into effect, pulling out of that agreement on the pretext of novel demands such as the cessation of all KORUS military drills or for the South Korean government to censor conservative anti-North Korea activists and defectors, demands the North knew the South would be unable to fulfill. Another frequently deployed tactic was to manufacture a crisis and then demand a reward for deescalation. Thus, North-South and North-US relations have taken on a cyclical characteristic in which periods of controlled hostility alternate with periods of relative peace, but always pulling back from the brink whenever the situation gets too close to either pole. The theory that best explains this historical evidence is that Pyongyang's strategists favor neither peace nor war but rather maintenance of a status quo of semi-hostility in order to continue to justify the country's seige mentality and it's continuous failure to provide for the material well-being of its citizens.

Neutral countries (Sweden, Switzerland) provide more cover for both parties, along with an air of international support. ROK is an option as the broker, as is the DMZ. China and Mongolia are long shots, given the optics. Russia is a no-go, at least if the WH has any desire not to bring down unnecessary scrutiny. It's unlikely the US would invite Kim onto its soil. International waters is logistically difficult, as any government vessel is considered sovereign territory of that nation (i.e., meeting on a US aircraft carrier is equivalent to meeting on a US installation overseas, which is considered US sovereign territory, meaning its the same as stepping foot on US soil for legal reasons). Somewhere else, maybe, but then you're getting into the "who's friends with whom" game, and that's can get unnecessarily complicated.
